Obtaining Default Gateway & Interface

Parse /proc/net/route — no subprocess needed:

C++

#include <fstream>
#include <sstream>
#include <optional>
#include <arpa/inet.h>

struct DefaultRoute {
    std::string iface;    // "eth0", "wlp2s0", etc.
    std::string gateway;  // "192.168.1.1"
};

std::optional<DefaultRoute> get_default_route() {
    std::ifstream f("/proc/net/route");
    if (!f) return std::nullopt;

    std::string line;
    std::getline(f, line); // skip header

    while (std::getline(f, line)) {
        std::istringstream iss(line);
        std::string iface, dest_hex, gw_hex;
        iss >> iface >> dest_hex >> gw_hex;

        if (dest_hex == "00000000") {            // default route
            uint32_t gw = std::stoul(gw_hex, nullptr, 16);
            struct in_addr addr;
            addr.s_addr = gw;                    // already correct byte order
            return DefaultRoute{ iface, inet_ntoa(addr) };
        }
    }
    return std::nullopt;
}

The hex values in /proc/net/route are the raw __be32 from the kernel — same representation as s_addr, so no ntohl needed.
Your TUN Creation Code

It's correct, but you're missing bringing the interface up. Without that none of the routes will work. Also check fcntl return:

C++

if (fcntl(fd, F_SETFL, O_NONBLOCK) < 0) {
    close(fd);
    cuabort("failed to set non-blocking");
}

Full Route Setup

C++

void setup_routes(const std::string& server_ip, const std::string& vpn_client_ip) {
    auto route = get_default_route();
    if (!route) cuabort("no default route found");

    auto cmd = [](const std::string& c) {
        if (std::system(c.c_str()) != 0)
            cuabort("command failed: " + c);
    };

    // 1. bring tun up (REQUIRED — you're missing this)
    cmd("ip link set tun0 up");

    // 2. assign address
    cmd("ip addr add " + vpn_client_ip + "/16 dev tun0");

    // 3. pin real server via original gateway so it doesn't go into the tunnel
    cmd("ip route add " + server_ip + "/32 via " + route->gateway + " dev " + route->iface);

    // 4. hijack all traffic into tunnel (two halves avoid replacing the default route)
    cmd("ip route add 0.0.0.0/1 via " + vpn_client_ip + " dev tun0");
    cmd("ip route add 128.0.0.0/1 via " + vpn_client_ip + " dev tun0");
}

And teardown (important — otherwise you brick networking on exit/crash):

C++

void teardown_routes(const std::string& server_ip, const std::string& vpn_client_ip) {
    // reverse order; ignore errors on cleanup
    std::system("ip route del 128.0.0.0/1 via ...");
    std::system("ip route del 0.0.0.0/1 via ...");
    std::system(("ip route del " + server_ip + "/32").c_str());
    std::system("ip link set tun0 down");
}

Register it with a signal handler or atexit, or you'll lose connectivity if the process dies.
Order of Operations

text

open(/dev/net/tun)
  → ioctl TUNSETIFF
  → fcntl O_NONBLOCK
  → wrap in asio stream_descriptor
  → ip link set tun0 up          ← you were missing this
  → ip addr add ...
  → ip route add server pinning
  → ip route add 0/1
  → ip route add 128/1
  → start reading/writing on the fd

The TUN fd won't produce or accept packets until the interface is up and has an address.
